{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_018a8zUtKJgTLgwdFN3QUEBc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to write a test plan for a spreadsheet formula engine. I need to analyze each of the 10 behaviors and determine the minimum test infrastructure needed to catch a real failure for each one.\n\nLet me think through the LEVEL-DEFS:\n- **Unit** — one local function or object boundary, no I/O\n- **Integration** — several modules wired together, local DB or filesystem\n- **System** — subprocess, OS behavior, real HTTP, or real external API call\n- **Agentic** — result depends on real LLM non-determinism or a real AI/ML model call\n- **Workflow** — multiple agentic steps in sequence, or a full agent pipeline\n\nNote: This is a spreadsheet engine, not an LLM-dependent system. So Agentic and Workflow are unlikely to apply here unless there's something I'm missing.\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: SUM function**\n- \"A cell containing `=SUM(A1:A10)` evaluates to the correct sum of the values in cells A1 through A10.\"\n- This is testing the SUM function's core logic. The failure boundary is: does the SUM function correctly aggregate a range?\n- **Could a mock miss this?** If you mock the range lookup, you might miss bugs in how the SUM function iterates. But actually, the main thing to test is: does the evaluator correctly parse `SUM(A1:A10)` and pass the right range, and does the SUM function correctly sum?\n- **Real infrastructure needed?** The evaluator needs to know about cells A1:A10 and their values. You need a spreadsheet with those cells populated.\n- This is **Unit** if you're just testing the SUM function in isolation with a mock range. But to catch real failures in how the evaluator wires SUM to the actual cell values, you need **Integration** — several modules (evaluator, cell storage, SUM function) wired together.\n\n\n- Testing just the SUM function with a hardcoded list would miss bugs in range parsing, cell lookup, and evaluation sequencing. You need the full pipeline—parser, evaluator, and cell storage—working together to catch real failures.\n\n**Behavior 2:**\n- When a cell references another cell containing a formula (like `=B1+1` where B1 holds `=A1*2`), the result must reflect the cascaded evaluation. This requires the parser to handle the reference, the evaluator to recursively resolve B1's formula, and arithmetic to execute correctly. A unit test of addition alone won't expose issues with recursive evaluation or cell resolution order. Multiple components must integrate properly.\n\n**Behavior 3:**\n- Detecting circular dependencies (A1 → B1 → A1) and returning an error instead of infinite looping tests the cycle detection mechanism. Mocking out cell lookups could hide this entirely—you need actual cell references to trigger the detection logic.\n\n**Behavior 4:**\n- VLOOKUP with exact match must return the correct value from a lookup table and error when the key doesn't exist. Mocking the table risks missing bugs in search logic or error handling. The real test requires an actual lookup table wired to the VLOOKUP function.\n\n**Behavior 5:**\n- Nested IF conditions like `=IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\")` need the IF function, condition evaluation, and cell references all integrated to catch parsing or evaluation bugs that mocks would hide.\n\n**Behavior 6:**\n- CONCATENATE should skip empty cells and apply the correct separator. Mocking cell values could miss how the function actually handles empty cells versus blank strings, so the real failure boundary requires testing with actual empty cells.\n\n**Behavior 7:**\n- Cross-sheet references like `=Sheet2!A1+1` demand multiple sheets, parser support for the `Sheet2!A1` syntax, sheet lookup logic, and cell resolution all working together. Unit testing the parser alone won't catch bugs in sheet lookup or reference evaluation.\n\n**Behavior 8:**\n- When a referenced cell changes, dependent formulas must recalculate in the correct topological order. This requires the dependency graph and recalculation engine to function as a unified system—mocking either one would hide ordering bugs.\n\n**Behavior 9:**\n- Undo must restore both the formula text and all dependent cell values. This involves formula storage, dependent value tracking, and undo state management working in concert. Mocking any of these components would mask failures in how the undo state is preserved and restored.\n\n**Behavior 10:**\n- Saving and reloading a workbook must preserve cell values and formulas exactly, including floating-point precision. This is fundamentally a serialization test—the binary format itself is the failure boundary. While disk I/O could theoretically be mocked, the real bugs live in format encoding, precision handling, and deserialization logic, which require testing the actual serialization pathway to catch reliably. The key failures to catch are serialization bugs, deserialization bugs, and floating-point precision issues—all of which require Integration testing with actual serialization and deserialization. Disk corruption would need System testing, but that's not part of the stated behavior. Since the requirement is just verifying round-trip data integrity without mentioning file system errors, Integration testing with in-memory or temporary file I/O is sufficient to validate the workbook saves and loads correctly. The distinction between Integration and System tests hinges on what's being tested—Integration tests can use the real filesystem through temporary files, while System tests involve external processes or APIs. For this persistence layer, Integration seems most appropriate since you're testing the filesystem without external dependencies.\n\nThe core question isn't about traditional categorization but about what's minimally necessary to catch actual failures. For the workbook scenario—saving,