ies exist, which they don't here. So I'm most confident Integration is the minimum (0.8), with smaller chances that Unit suffices (0.1) or System is required (0.1).\n\nBut I might be underestimating Unit's capability if the SUM function is straightforward and the evaluator is solid, or overestimating if there are OS-level factors I'm missing. Let me reconsider by assigning probabilities differently: Unit represents the likelihood it's sufficient alone, Integration the likelihood it's needed but System isn't, System the likelihood it's needed but Agentic isn't, and so on. For a spreadsheet without LLM involvement, Agentic and Workflow testing are minimal concerns (0.01-0.05 each). For the SUM function specifically, Unit testing wouldn't catch evaluator-to-cell wiring bugs, making Integration the more probable minimum level.\n\nFor cascaded references, the real risk is recursive evaluation failures that mocked cell lookups won't expose, so Integration becomes the likely threshold. Circular dependency detection is trickier—unit tests of the cycle logic might miss infinite recursion issues that only surface during actual evaluation, though Integration testing with circular cells should catch most problems. System testing might reveal stack overflow or resource exhaustion scenarios that Integration misses.\n\nVLOOKUP and nested IF functions both have similar patterns: unit tests with mock data can't replicate how these functions interact with actual cell data and formula parsing, making Integration tests the critical layer. CONCATENATE with empty cells presents a comparable challenge—the function's behavior with actual empty cells differs from testing with empty strings, so Integration testing becomes essential to validate the interaction.\n\nCross-sheet references require Integration testing across multiple sheets to catch failures that unit tests of the parser alone would miss. Recalculation in topological order similarly depends on Integration tests with dependent cells to verify the evaluator processes formulas in the correct sequence. For undo operations, unit tests with mocked state can't capture all failure modes, so Integration testing becomes the primary validation mechanism.\n\nPersistence testing shows slightly different probabilities—unit tests of serialization logic with in-memory buffers might catch some issues, making it 0.2 likely to be sufficient, while Integration tests with actual disk I/O are more reliable at 0.75. System-level testing could reveal OS-specific concerns like file corruption, though this is less probable at 0.05.\n\nI need to reconsider the framework—the instructions ask for 5 levels of confidence: Unit, Integration, System, Agentic, and Workflow. Since this is a spreadsheet engine without LLM involvement, Agentic and Workflow probabilities should be minimal. Let me redistribute across all five levels. For most behaviors, Unit tests have low confidence (0.05), Integration tests are strong (0.9), System tests catch edge cases (0.04), while Agentic and Workflow each contribute only 0.005 to the total. This pattern holds across behaviors 1-3, with behavior 4 starting similarly before being cut off. - Unit: 0.05\n- Integration: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic: 0.005\n- Workflow: 0.005\n- Total: 1.0 ✓\n\nFor behavior 6:\n- Unit: 0.1\n- Integration: 0.85\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic: 0.005\n- Workflow: 0.005\n- Total: 1.0 ✓\n\nFor behavior 7:\n- Unit: 0.05\n- Integration: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic: 0.005\n- Workflow: 0.005\n- Total: 1.0 ✓\n\nFor behavior 8:\n- Unit: 0.05\n- Integration: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic: 0.005\n- Workflow: 0.005\n- Total: 1.0 ✓\n\nFor behavior 9:\n- Unit: 0.05\n- Integration: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic: 0.005\n- Workflow: 0.005\n- Total: 1.0 ✓\n\nFor behavior 10:\n- Unit: 0.15\n- Integration: 0.8\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic: 0.005\n- Workflow: 0.005\n- Total: 1.0 ✓\n\nNow I'll document the test descriptions and justifications for each behavior.\n\n**Behavior 1: SUM function**\n- Description: \"Verify that a SUM formula correctly aggregates values from a range by creating a worksheet with cells A1:A10 containing specific numeric values, entering a SUM formula, and asserting the result matches the expected sum.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"Testing SUM in isolation won't reveal bugs in range parsing (A1:A10) or cell reference resolution. The actual failure point emerges when the evaluator connects the SUM function to real cell data, requiring parser, cell storage, and function modules to work together.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, the test description requires the Integration level.\n\n**Behavior 2: Cascaded formula references**\n- Description: \"Verify cascaded evaluation by creating a worksheet where A1=5, B1=A1*2 (expected 10), and C1=B1+1 (expected 11), then asserting that C1 evaluates to 11.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"A unit test of individual formulas won't catch issues in how the evaluator chains references across cells. The critical failure boundary is where dependent formulas resolve their upstream references correctly, which demands integration testing with the full evaluation pipeline.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, the test description requires the Integration level.\n\n**Behavior 3: Circular dependency detection**\n- Description: \"Verify that circular references are detected by creating a worksheet where A1 contains =B1 and B1 contains =A1, then asserting that evaluating either cell returns a circular reference error without entering infinite recursion.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"The risk we're protecting against is infinite recursion or stack overflow. Mocking cycle detection logic won't exercise the actual evaluator's call stack under real circular conditions. We need genuine formula evaluation with actual circular references to confirm the cycle detector activates and prevents recursion.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration to verify the actual evaluator behavior.\n\n**Behavior 4: VLOOKUP with exact match**\n- Description: \"Create a lookup table (multiple cells) with key-value pairs, use VLOOKUP to search for an existing key, and verify the correct value is returned; also test VLOOKUP with a non-existent key and verify an error is returned.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"VLOOKUP's correctness hinges on how it retrieves values from the actual cell table and interprets the range parameter. Testing the lookup algorithm alone won't expose bugs in cell value retrieval or range handling. Integration testing with real cells and actual lookup operations is essential.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration to verify the actual evaluator behavior.\n\n**Behavior 5: Nested IF conditions**\n- Description: \"Create a worksheet with A1 containing various test values (5, 15, 25) and test a nested IF formula that returns different strings based on thresholds, verifying correct branches are taken.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"Nested IF evaluation depends on correct formula parsing and proper conditional branching. Unit testing the IF logic won't catch parser bugs with nested structures or issues with condition short-circuiting. Integration testing ensures the parser and evaluator coordinate properly.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration to verify the actual evaluator behavior.\n\n**Behavior 6: CONCATENATE with empty cells**\n- Description: \"Create cells with a mix of non-empty and empty values, use CONCATENATE to join them with a separator, and verify that empty cells are skipped (not contributing blank strings) and the result is correctly separated.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"CONCATENATE's behavior with empty cells depends on how the evaluator reads cell values and how the function processes them. Unit testing the concatenation logic won't reveal bugs in how empty cells are handled during actual evaluation. Integration testing with real cells ensures the function behaves correctly with actual data.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration to verify the actual evaluator behavior.\n\n**Behavior 7: Cross-sheet references**\n- Description: \"Create multiple sheets (Sheet1, Sheet2), put a value in Sheet2!A1, create a formula in Sheet1 that references =Sheet2!A1+1, and verify the formula resolves correctly.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"Cross-sheet references require the parser to handle sheet name syntax and the evaluator to perform lookups across sheet boundaries. Unit testing the parser alone won't catch bugs in how references are resolved across sheets. Integration testing with actual multi-sheet setup is necessary.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration to verify the actual evaluator behavior.\n\n**Behavior 8: Recalculation in topological order**\n- Description: \"Create a chain of dependent formulas (A1=5, B1=A1*2, C1=B1+1), change A1's value, and verify that B1 and C1 are recalculated in the correct order with correct final values.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"Recalculation order depends on the evaluator's ability to track dependencies and update cells in the right sequence. Unit testing individual formula evaluation won't catch bugs in dependency tracking or update ordering. Integration testing with actual dependent formulas ensures the system maintains correct values across the chain.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration to verify the actual evaluator behavior.\n\n**Behavior 9: Undo operation**\n- Description: \"Create a worksheet with formulas, edit a formula, verify the new formula is in place, trigger undo, and assert that both the formula text and all dependent cell values are restored to their previous state.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"Undo coordinates multiple systems—formula storage, evaluation, dependency tracking, and state history. Unit testing undo logic with mocked state won't catch bugs in how state is captured and restored across all affected cells. Integration testing with real formulas and dependencies ensures the complete undo flow works correctly.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration to verify the actual evaluator behavior.\n\n**Behavior 10: Persistence**\n- Description: \"Create a worksheet with a mix of formulas and values including floating-point numbers, serialize it to the binary format, deserialize it, and verify that all cell values, formulas, and floating-point precision are identical.\"\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: \"Serialization and deserialization span multiple modules and require actual I/O. Unit tests of individual serialization functions won't catch precision loss or format bugs in how floating-point numbers are encoded or fields are round-tripped. Integration testing with real file I/O is necessary.\"\n- Plan consistent: Yes, this requires Integration.\n\nI should reconsider the level_probabilities more carefully. Different behaviors likely have different distributions rather than similar ones across the board.\n\n**Behavior 1: SUM function**\n- Unit testing with a mock range might catch most bugs, but could miss issues in how the parser constructs the range object. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.1\n- Integration is most likely: 0.85\n- System could apply if OS-level behavior is involved: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 2: Cascaded formula references**\n- Unit testing won't work here since you need the evaluator to recursively resolve references. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.05\n- Integration is most likely: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 3: Circular dependency detection**\n- Unit testing the cycle detection algorithm with mocked dependencies might work, but the real failure is infinite recursion. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.15\n- Integration is most likely: 0.8\n- System could be needed if stack overflow behavior varies by OS: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 4: VLOOKUP with exact match**\n- Unit testing is unlikely to suffice since you need actual cell data. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.1\n- Integration is most likely: 0.85\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 5: Nested IF conditions**\n- Unit testing won't work because you need the parser and evaluator working together. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.05\n- Integration is most likely: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 6: CONCATENATE with empty cells**\n- Unit testing with null/empty values might work, but the real issue is how actual empty cells behave. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.2\n- Integration is most likely: 0.75\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 7: Cross-sheet references**\n- Unit testing won't work because you need multiple sheets and a lookup mechanism. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.05\n- Integration is most likely: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 8: Recalculation in topological order**\n- Unit testing is unlikely since you need multiple dependent cells. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.05\n- Integration is most likely: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 9: Undo operation**\n- Unit testing won't work because you need the full system state and history management. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.05\n- Integration is most likely: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each\n\n**Behavior 10: Persistence**\n- Unit testing individual serialization functions won't catch precision loss or encoding bugs. Probability Unit is minimum: 0.05\n- Integration is most likely: 0.9\n- System: 0.04\n- Agentic/Workflow: 0.005 each file permissions, or corruption. The behavior focuses on data integrity—no missing fields, no precision loss, no format incompatibility—which in-memory serialization can verify without actual file I/O. A unit test could catch these issues by testing serialization of individual cells and values directly, so Integration seems appropriate here, though it's a close call.\n\nUnit tests might miss subtle bugs in field ordering, alignment, or how the full workbook structure is preserved during serialization. Integration testing is more likely to surface these real-world failures. I'll adjust the probabilities slightly toward Unit since the core issue is serialization logic rather than module interactions: Unit at 0.25, Integration at 0.7, System at 0.04, and Agentic/Workflow at 0.005 each.\n\nI should finalize these estimates rather than continue refining them. Here are my probability assignments across all behaviors:\n\n1. SUM: Unit 0.1, Integration 0.85, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n2. Cascaded: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.9, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n3. Circular: Unit 0.15, Integration 0.8, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n4. VLOOKUP: Unit 0.1, Integration 0.85, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n5. Nested IF: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.9, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n6. CONCATENATE: Unit 0.2, Integration 0.75, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n7. Cross-sheet: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.9, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n8. Recalculation: Unit 0.05, Integration 0\n\n.9, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n9. Undo: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.9, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n10. Persistence: Unit 0.2, Integration 0.75, System 0.04, Agentic 0.005, Workflow 0.005\n\nBefore structuring the output, I need to double-check the plan_consistent field. The self-check requires me to verify that each test_description actually demands the minimum_level I assigned, not just passes at that level. If a test could succeed at a lower level, I should adjust plan_consistent accordingly.\n\nGoing through each behavior: SUM requires Integration since cells and range resolution need actual interaction—mocking wouldn't capture the real behavior. Cascaded formulas with interdependencies also need Integration to verify the evaluation chain works correctly. Circular references specifically test for infinite recursion, which only manifests when the evaluator processes the cells, making Integration necessary. VLOOKUP involves a lookup table and needs the full evaluation context to work properly.\n\nNested IF, CONCATENATE with mixed empty values, and cross-sheet references all depend on the evaluator actually processing cells and formulas, so Integration is required for each. Recalculation tests value propagation through dependent cells—this can't be verified without seeing the full system respond to changes. Undo needs the complete system to track and reverse edits. Persistence tests the round-trip serialization and deserialization of a workbook, which requires Integration to validate the full cycle works end-to-end.\n\nAll ten behaviors consistently require Integration testing rather than Unit testing.\n\nNow I need to define specific, testable descriptions for each test case. For SUM, I'll create cells A1 through A10 with values 1-10, place a SUM formula in A11, and verify it evaluates to 55. Cascaded formulas should set A1=5, then B1=A1*2 and C1=B1+1, confirming B1 becomes 10 and C1 becomes 11. Circular references should attempt to create A1=B1 and B1=A1, then verify the system detects and returns a circular reference error without hanging. VLOOKUP needs a lookup table set up in specific cells with a formula that retrieves values based on a key.\n\nFor the VLOOKUP test, I'll create a lookup table in A1:B5 with keys in column A and corresponding values in column B. One VLOOKUP formula should find an existing key and return the correct value, while another should search for a non-existent key and return the #N/A error. The nested IF test requires a formula that evaluates A1 against multiple thresholds—returning \"high\" when A1>20, \"medium\" when A1>10, and \"low\" otherwise—tested with values 25, 15, and 5. CONCATENATE should combine values from A1:A4 (including empty cells) with commas between them, producing \"hello,,world,\" or handling empty cells according to the implementation's behavior. The cross-sheet test will reference data from Sheet1 in formulas on another sheet.\n\nFor Sheet2, I'll create a formula that references Sheet1!A1 and adds 1 to it, expecting the result to be 6 when Sheet1!A1 contains 5. The recalculation test sets up a chain where B1 multiplies A1 by 2 and C1 adds 1 to B1, then changes A1 to verify both dependent cells update automatically. Undo functionality should restore a formula from =A1*B1 back to =A1+B1 and recalculate the result. Finally, persistence testing will save a workbook containing mixed formulas and floating-point values to binary format, then reload it to confirm all data is preserved.\n\nThese test cases are concrete and measurable. I should now refine the justifications to read like a technical review—focusing on why integration testing catches bugs that unit tests miss. For SUM, a unit test with mocked ranges won't expose issues in how the parser builds range objects or connects the evaluator to actual cell storage; those bugs only surface when the parser, evaluator, and cell layer interact. The cascaded formula test similarly requires all three components working together to verify that dependent cells recalculate correctly when inputs change.\n\nFor circular references, the concern is stack overflow during actual recursive evaluation—something a unit test of cycle detection alone can't trigger. And VLOOKUP needs to read from real cells in a table to verify it finds the correct row and column intersection.\n\nNested IF statements require both correct AST parsing and proper branch short-circuiting, which only shows up when evaluating cells with conditional values. CONCATENATE's behavior with empty cells depends on how the function interprets actual spreadsheet data, not just string 